<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920306-0070</DOCNO><DOCID>920306-0070.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Coltec Holdings Inc.:   Junk Bond Holders Clear   Way for Recapitalization</HL><DATE>03/06/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   COT MS</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)INITIAL STOCK OFFERINGS (INI)SECURITIES (SCR)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, REPURCHASES, SWAPS (BBK)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS (INI)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Coltec Holdings Inc., preparing to go public, said it hasreceived enough tenders from holders of its junk bonds toproceed with its recapitalization.   The New York maker of aerospace, automotive and otherindustrial equipment said it received tenders and consentsfor more than two-thirds of its 14.75% senior discountdebentures. A majority was needed to amend the agreement forthe debenture issue that would allow Coltec to proceed withthe recapitalization.</LP><TEXT>   Coltec Holdings last month began the tender offer for thedebenture issue as part of its recapitalization, whichincludes a planned $577 million public stock offering and thenew Coltec Industries notes totaling $450 million. Coltecoffered to pay 107% of the aggregate value of the debentureson the day prior to payment. About $881 million face amountof the 14.75% issue is outstanding.   The company, formerly Colt Industries Inc., was acquiredfor $660 million in 1988 by Morgan Stanley andamp; Co. andaffiliates.</TEXT></DOC>